faqs:
  - q: "What is the best puppy food in the UK?"
    a: "Our top pick is Forthglade. Its cold-pressed dry food is rated 73–75% by All About Dog Food and its wet trays 77–88% — among the highest puppy scores in the UK — and uniquely it's all-life-stage, so the same grain-free recipe carries from weaning right through to senior with no stressful diet switches as your pup grows. For fresh feeding, Butternut Box (93–94% AADF) and Years (95% AADF) lead on nutrition; Pooch & Mutt is the best-value grain-free kibble."
  - q: "How is puppy food different from adult dog food?"
    a: "Puppies grow fast and need more energy, protein, calcium and phosphorus per kilo than adults, plus DHA for brain and eye development. Reputable puppy and all-life-stage foods are formulated to FEDIAF/AAFCO growth standards. Large and giant breeds especially need carefully balanced calcium and controlled calorie density, because overfeeding and rapid growth raise the risk of joint and skeletal problems. Always check the food states it's suitable for growth or all life stages."
  - q: "How much should I feed my puppy and how often?"
    a: "Follow the feeding guide on the pack for your puppy's age and expected adult weight, and split it across more meals than an adult: roughly four meals a day to around 4 months, three meals to about 6 months, then two meals from there. Puppies have small stomachs and fast metabolisms, so little and often is best. Weigh portions rather than eyeballing them — steady growth beats fast growth, particularly for larger breeds."
  - q: "When should I switch my puppy to adult food?"
    a: "It depends on size. Small breeds typically move to adult food around 9–12 months, medium breeds around 12 months, and large or giant breeds not until 18–24 months because they keep growing for longer. The simplest route is an all-life-stage food like Forthglade or a fresh brand that adjusts portions automatically — then there's no abrupt switch at all. When you do change, transition over 7–10 days."
  - q: "Is grain-free food safe for puppies?"
    a: "Grain-free is fine for most puppies, but it's worth understanding the nuance. The heart-health concern raised in recent years (dilated cardiomyopathy) has been linked to some grain-free recipes that lean heavily on peas, lentils and other pulses as replacements — it's the legume load and recipe balance under scrutiny, not the absence of grain itself. Choosing a well-formulated brand matters more than the grain-free label. Years, for example, is both grain- and legume-free. If your puppy has no diagnosed grain sensitivity, a quality wholegrain food is also perfectly healthy — ask your vet if unsure."
  - q: "Should I feed my puppy wet, dry or fresh food?"
    a: "All three can support healthy growth if they meet growth nutritional standards. Dry kibble is cheapest and convenient; cold-pressed dry (like Forthglade) is gentler on digestion than standard extruded kibble. Wet and fresh foods are more palatable and hydrating — useful for fussy or teething pups — but cost more. Many owners do a mix. The most important factors are that the food is complete for growth, suits your puppy's breed size, and that you control portions to avoid overfeeding."
  - q: "How much does feeding a puppy cost per day?"
    a: "It varies widely with breed size and food type. Grain-free kibble like Pooch & Mutt can be around £0.45/day for a small pup; cold-pressed Forthglade from roughly £0.70/day; air-dried Pure Pet Food from about £0.89/day; and chilled fresh Butternut Box around £2.40/day for a small growing pup, rising with size. Buying dry food in larger bags or fresh food on subscription usually lowers the per-day cost."
  - q: "Why does portion control matter so much for puppies?"
    a: "Because how fast a puppy grows affects its joints for life. Overfeeding — especially large and giant breeds — drives rapid growth that's linked to hip and elbow dysplasia and other skeletal problems. Lean, steady growth is healthier. This is one reason we rate the fresh subscriptions (Butternut Box, Years, Pure) for puppies: they pre-portion meals to your pup's current weight and growth target and adjust as they grow, taking the guesswork out."
