<h2>What Makes a Good Puppy Food</h2>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Formulated for growth</strong> — The food must state it's suitable for growth or all life stages (FEDIAF/AAFCO complete). Adult-only recipes don't carry the protein, calcium and DHA a growing pup needs.</li>
  <li><strong>Balanced calcium &amp; controlled energy</strong> — Especially for large and giant breeds, where excess calcium or over-rich food drives rapid growth linked to joint and skeletal problems.</li>
  <li><strong>High, named meat content</strong> — Real, named meat over vague "meat and animal derivatives". Forthglade, Butternut Box and Years all lead here.</li>
  <li><strong>Gentle on developing digestion</strong> — Hypoallergenic, no artificial additives, and ideally grain-free or wholegrain rather than cheap cereal fillers. Cold-pressed and fresh formats are gentler than standard extruded kibble.</li>
  <li><strong>The right size and texture</strong> — Small pellets or soft, rehydrated/wet food suit tiny mouths and teething pups.</li>
  <li><strong>Portion control built in</strong> — The fresh subscriptions pre-portion to your pup's weight and growth target, which removes the single biggest feeding mistake: overfeeding.</li>
</ul>

