<h2>Wet vs Dry vs Fresh for Puppies</h2>

<p>Each format can support healthy growth — what matters is that it's complete for growth and portioned correctly:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Dry food (kibble)</strong> — Cheapest and most convenient. Cold-pressed dry (Forthglade) is gentler on digestion than standard extruded kibble. See our <a href="/best-grain-free-dog-food-uk/">best grain-free dry food guide</a>.</li>
  <li><strong>Wet food</strong> — High moisture and very palatable, ideal for teething or fussy pups, but pricier per calorie. See our <a href="/best-grain-free-wet-dog-food-uk/">best grain-free wet food guide</a>.</li>
  <li><strong>Fresh food</strong> — Gently cooked whole ingredients, the biggest step up in quality, with portions tailored to growth. See our <a href="/best-fresh-dog-food-uk/">best fresh dog food guide</a>.</li>
  <li><strong>All-life-stage</strong> — A food like Forthglade that suits puppy through senior means no stressful diet switch as your dog matures.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Feeding and Transitioning a Puppy</h2>

<p>Feed little and often — roughly four meals a day to around 4 months, three to about 6 months, then two from there. Always weigh portions against the pack guide for your pup's age and expected adult weight; steady growth beats fast growth, especially for larger breeds. When switching foods (or moving to adult food later — around 12 months for small/medium breeds, 18–24 months for large/giant), transition over <strong>7–10 days</strong>, mixing increasing amounts of the new food each day to avoid tummy upset. As your dog ages, our <a href="/best-senior-dog-food-uk/">best senior dog food guide</a> picks up where this one leaves off. If appetite, weight or toileting changes noticeably and doesn't settle, book a vet check.</p>

